Passive recording with SM4
Bird sitting on ground.

3 different call types: 

* a classic, straight call at 0:01

* three more buzzing calls from 0:03.7 on

* vague, short calls from 0:05.05 on.

Recorded:

  • flight call, pssiiiip, bsiii or pssih, at 0:02.7
  • flight call (in flock), lower pitched, psü, psiyi or psili, at 0:05.6 and 0:08.9

General observations: Fields along a ditch with reeds and willows. Partly sunny. Temperature: 9°C/48.2°F. No wind.

Recording remarks: (Probably) more than one Red-throated pipit is calling while flying. Cofta (2021) recognizes that in flock Red-throated Pipits call with a markedly lower-pitched sound (see above) compared with the common flight call.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Canada Goose, Branta canadensis, call, rorr-rorr, at 0:04.2 (vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: Cofta, 2021, Flight Identification of European Passerines, WildGuides; NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Sony PCM-A10 Recorder

  • song (part of), svü-svü-svü-svü wi-wi-wi-wi tsvü-tsvü-tsvü, at 0:35.4

General observations: High grasses on moisty ground close to a shallow flatland lake. Distant traffic on a middle-sized country road. Red-throated pipit (probably a male based on rusty-red throat) flies over grasses calling. Thereafter calls and sing faintly when perched in a small bush.

  • Spotted Redshank, Tringa erythropus, flight call, chu-it, at 0:21.5 (vaguely)
  • Hooded Crow, Corvus cornix, call, krrrah, at e.g. 0:40.6 (vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: Svensson, Mullarney and Zetterström, 2009, Collins Bird Guide, Second Edition, HarperCollinsPublishers
